sed","1091–1130":"1091–1130","1091":"1091","BEF 1120":"before 1120","6 MAY 1130":"6 May 1130","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","ABT 1091":"about 1091","1092":"1092","of,Sponheim,Rheinland,Prussia":"Sponheim, Kreuznach, Rhineland, Prussia","Deutschland":"Germany","Liebenau, Freistadt, Upper Austria":"Liebenau, Freistadt, Upper Austria, Austria","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Siegfried","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>sige</i> ‘victory’ + <i>frid</i> ‘peace’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["North American: from the title originally adopted as a nickname parallel to   Duke  ,   King  , etc. The title was used in England in Norman times as an equivalent of the French <i>comte</i> ‘count’ it is from Old English <i>eorl</i> ‘warrior, nobleman, prince’. In some cases the given name may have been taken from the surname <i>Earl</i>, which was originally either a nickname or a term denoting someone who worked in the household of an earl."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Ivo  , derived from the oblique case of the name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Arch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname. This has two origins: as a local name for someone who lived on the border between two territories, especially in the Marches between England and Wales or England and Scotland (from Norman French <i>march</i> ‘boundary’, of Germanic origin); and as a nickname for someone with some association with the month of March (Old French <i>march(e)</i>, Latin <i>(mensis) Martius</i>, a derivative of <i>Mars</i>;  compare  Martin  ). In part this name may also have been adopted as a first name by association with the female names   April  ,   May  , and   June  , bearing in mind that Mars, the roman god of war, after whom the month is named, is male."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Siegfried I Count von Arch Sponheim was born about 1091, in Sponheim, Kreuznach, Rhineland, Prussia. He had at least 2 sons with Hildburg von Tengling. He died on 6 May 1130, in Liebenau, Freistadt, Upper Austria, Austria, at the age of 40."},"et":{"ABT 1091–6 MAY 1130":"umbes 1091–6. mai 1130","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1120–1164":"1120–1164","–Male":"Surnud","1091–1130":"1091–1130","1091":"1091","BEF 1120":"enne 1120","6 MAY 1130":"6. mai 1130","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","ABT 1091":"umbes 1091","1092":"1092","of,Sponheim,Rheinland,Prussia":"Sponheim, Kreuznach, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Deutschland":"Saksamaa","Liebenau, Freistadt, Upper Austria":"Liebenau, Freistadt, Oberösterreich, Austria"},"fi":{"ABT 1091–6 MAY 1130":"noin 1091–6. toukokuuta 1130","1092–Female":"1092–Kuollut","1120–1164":"1120–1164","–Male":"Kuollut","1091–1130":"1091–1130","1091":"1091","BEF 1120":"ennen vuotta 1120","6 MAY 1130":"6. toukokuuta 1130","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","ABT 1091":"noin 1091","1092":"1092","of,Sponheim,Rheinland,Prussia":"Sponheim, Kreuznach, Rheinprovinz, Preußen","Deutschland":"Saksa","Liebenau, Freistadt, Upper Austria":"Liebenau, Freistadt, Oberösterreich, Itävalta"},"fr":{"ABT 1091–6 MAY 1130":"environ 1091–6 mai 1130","1092–Female":"1092–Décédée","1120–1164":"1120–1164","–Male":"Décédé","1091–1130":"1091–1130","1091":"1091","BEF 1120":"avant 1120","6 MAY 1130":"6 mai 1130","1164":"1164","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","ABT 1091":"environ 1091","1092":"1092","of,Sponhe